label.value: decreased error-free translesion synthesis of cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the repair of cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers by error-free translesion synthesis occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: normal error-free translesion synthesis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which error-free translesion synthesis is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Error-free translesion synthesis a DNA repair process that results in the conversion of DNA-damage induced single-stranded gaps into large molecular weight DNA after replication by using a specialized DNA polymerase or replication complex to insert a defined nucleotide across from the lesion.

label.value: normal error-prone translesion synthesis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which error-prone translesion synthesis is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Error-prone translesion synthesis a DNA repair process that results in the conversion of DNA-damage induced single-stranded gaps into large molecular weight DNA after replication.

label.value: abolished error-free translesion synthesis of cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the repair of cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers by error-free translesion synthesis does not occur.

label.value: normal error-free translesion synthesis of cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the repair of cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers by error-free translesion synthesis is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal error-free translesion synthesis of pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the repair of pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts by error-free translesion synthesis is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased error-free translesion synthesis of pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the repair of pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts by error-free translesion synthesis occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: decreased error-prone translesion synthesis of pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the repair of pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts by error-prone translesion synthesis occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: abolished error-prone translesion synthesis of pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the repair of pyrimidine-pyrimidone 6-4 photoproducts by error-prone translesion synthesis does not occur.

label.value: increased protein level during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased number of Holliday junctions

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the Holliday junctions is greater than normal. A Holliday junction is a structure where two DNA double strands are held together by reciprocal exchange of two of the four strands, one strand each from the two original helices.

definition.value: This phenotype can be detected by measuring the amount of DNA that migrates as X-shaped in two-dimensional agarose gels.

label.value: abnormal cell cycle arrest at mitotic G2/M phase transition during glucose starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through mitotic cell cycle arrest at the mitotic G2/M phase transition occurs abnormally when the cell is subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Cells normally arrest the mitotic cell cycle at the mitotic G2/M phase transition when subject to glucose starvation. Use this term if the G2 arrest does not occur exactly as in wild type cells. Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: normal level of histone H3 in cell

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of histone H3 measured in the cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased protein localization to nucleus during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is decreased during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to nucleus during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is increased during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal histone H4 deacetylation during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which deacetylation of lysine at position 4 of histone H4 is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

label.value: decreased chromatin binding during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of chromatin binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased during a cellular response to hydroxyurea. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene, and may normally bind DNA, protein, or both in chromatin.

label.value: normal rate of mitotic spindle elongation during anaphase B

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of mitotic spindle elongation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during anaphase B.

label.value: decreased rate of mitotic spindle elongation during anaphase B

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of mitotic spindle elongation is decreased during anaphase B.

label.value: abolished mitotic spindle midzone assembly

value.value: A microtubule cytoskeleton organization phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which formation of the mitotic spindle midzone, the area in the center of the mitotic spindle where the spindle microtubules from opposite poles overlap, does not occur.

label.value: mitotic sister chromatid separation during interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which mitotic sister chromatid separation begins during interphase of the cell cycle.

label.value: abolished protein localization to cytoplasm, with protein mislocalized to nucleus during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the cytoplasm is abolished, and the protein is instead present in the nucleus, during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: pointed nucleus during mitotic interphase

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the nucleus has a pointed shape during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: Nuclear chromatin within the nucleus also assumes a pointed shape, and the point is associated with the spindle pole body.

label.value: abnormal spindle pole body-led chromosome movement during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which spindle pole body (SPB)-led chromosome movement is abnormal. SPB-led chromosome movement is a microtubule-based process in which chromosomes migrate as a result of rapid spindle pole body (SPB) and centrosome oscillations during mitotic interphase.

label.value: increased spindle pole body-led chromosome movement during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the mitotic spindle pole body (SPB) moves rapidly back and forth to a greater extent and over a larger area than normal, causing increased chromosome movement. Normally, SPB oscillation occurs during mitotic interphase (as well as prophase) but is restricted to a small space.

label.value: abnormal chromatin organization resulting in peripheral chromatin distribution

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nuclear chromatin organization is abnormal, such that chromatin is distributed in a ring-shaped structure around the nuclear periphery rather than throughout the nucleus.

label.value: increased guanyl-nucleotide exchange factor activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate or other property of a guanyl-nucleotide exchange factor activity is abnormal.

definition.value: This term can mean that the mutated gene product itself has greater GEF activity than wild type, or that a mutation in one gene increases GEF activation by a second gene product. When using this term, it is therefore recommended to note the specific protein(s) affected.

label.value: normal attachment of mitotic spindle microtubules to kinetochore

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the physical attachment of sister chromatids to mitotic spindle microtubules is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal replication fork arrest at RTS1 barrier

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork arrest at the RTS1 barrier is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Note that the RTS1 barrier usually occurs in the mating type locus, but might be assayed at ectopic loci to maximise the distance that a restarted fork travels.

label.value: normal site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which site-specific DNA replication termination at the RTS1 barrier in the mating type region is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier in the mating type region is abnormal.

label.value: abolished site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier in the mating type region does not occur.

label.value: decreased site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier in the mating type region occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: increased site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which site-specific DNA replication termination at RTS1 barrier in the mating type region occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: normal termination of RNA polymerase II transcription at RTS1 barrier

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the termination of transcription by RNA polymerase II at the RTS1 replication fork barrier is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: reversed RTS1 barrier polarity

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the RTS1 replication termination site prevents replication fork movement in the opposite of normal direction. Normally, RTS1 acts as a barrier to replication forks moving in the cenII-distal direction.

label.value: increased level of large-Y replication intermediates

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the level of large Y-shaped DNA replication intermediates is greater than normal. Large Y-shaped intermediates are formed late in the passive replication of a DNA region by a replication fork moving from outside the region.

label.value: abnormal mitotic metaphase chromosome recapture

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromosome recapture is abnormal during metaphase of mitosis. Chromosome recapture is the reattachment of chromosomes which have become detached from the spindle.

label.value: decreased kinetochore microtubule depolymerization during mitotic metaphase chromosome recapture

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic spindle kinetochore microtubule depolymerization, occurs to a lesser extent than normal during mitotic chromosome recapture.

label.value: decreased rate of kinetochore sliding during chromosome recapture

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of kinetochore sliding, i.e. the movement of a kinetochore along spindle microtubules, during mitotic chromosome recapture is decreased.

definition.value: Note that, although the movement affected in this phenotype is often described as "kinetochore migration" or "kinetochore sliding", the entire chromosome moves along the spindle microtubules.

label.value: abolished kinetochore sliding during chromosome recapture

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which kinetochore sliding, i.e. the movement of a kinetochore along spindle microtubules, during mitotic chromosome recapture does not occur.

definition.value: Note that, although the movement affected in this phenotype is often described as "kinetochore migration" or "kinetochore sliding", the entire chromosome moves along the spindle microtubules.

label.value: abolished protein phosphorylation during mitosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, does not occur during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: inviable mononucleate aseptate cell with cell cycle arrest at mitotic G2/M phase transition

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is inviable, contains one nucleus, has no septum, and progression through the mitotic cell cycle is arrested at the mitotic G2/M phase transition.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: decreased level of iron ion starvation-induced proteins

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein encoded by genes normally induced during iron ion starvation measured in a cell is lower than normal.

label.value: abolished cell population growth at low temperature

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which a cell population does not grow at low temperatures.

definition.value: For fission yeast, low temperature usually corresponds to below 25 degrees Celsius. Use this term for a population of cells that does not grow at low temperature, but does grow at a higher temperature (a cell population that does not grow at any temperature would be considered inviable). Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: decreased fidelity of double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which occurrence of errors, usually small deletions, upon repair of double-strand breaks in DNA by nonhomologous end joining is increased.

definition.value: In wild type S. pombe cells, errors occur in 40-60% of NHEJ-mediated DSB repair events. In mutants with this phenotype, few or no repairs may be free of errors.

label.value: increased linear minichromosome loss during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype in which linear minichromosomes are lost at a higher frequency than normal during the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle. Minichromosome loss occurs when one or both daughter cells do not inherit copies of a minichromosome from the mother cell, and may result from failure of minichromosome replication or segregation.

label.value: increased circular minichromosome loss during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype in which circular minichromosomes are lost at a higher frequency than normal during the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle. Minichromosome loss occurs when one or both daughter cells do not inherit copies of a minichromosome from the mother cell, and may result from failure of minichromosome replication or segregation.

label.value: normal mitotic cell cycle regulation during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cellular response phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the regulation of the mitotic cell cycle in response to methyl methanesulfonate (MMS) is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Normally, cell cycle progression is slowed or arrested transiently following exposure to MMS.

label.value: decreased sister chromatid meiotic recombination

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of meiotic recombination between alleles of one sister chromatid (intra-sister recombination) or between alleles on different sister chromatids (inter-sister recombination) is decreased.
